<qandaentry><question><para> I'd like to see XYZ application in &KOffice;!</para></question>
<answer>
<para>
&KOffice; still lacks some applications that a complete office suite should offer. Some of them
 have been started or are being thought about (like a database or a project planning tool).
 But it doesn't make sense for all applications to use the &KOffice; libraries,
 so they aren't "&KOffice; applications". So if you're missing a
 certain application, you should take a look at the list of KDE applications you can
 find at <ulink url="http://apps.kde.com/">http://apps.kde.com/</ulink>.
 There's e.g. <application>KOrganizer</application>, a very sophisticated Organizer/Schedule program
 or <application>Quanta+</application>, a powerful HTML editor.
 If you think that a certain kind of application should be integrated into &KOffice;, contact
 <email>koffice at kde dot org</email>. </para>
</answer></qandaentry>

<qandaentry><question><para> What is the current state of &KOffice;?</para></question><answer>
<para>
&KOffice; has been released as 1.2. KOffice is released seperately
from the rest of KDE, so KOffice releases are not in sync with those of KDE.
</para>
</answer></qandaentry>

<qandaentry><question><para> Is &KOffice; stable? </para></question><answer>
<para>
The release versions of &KOffice; are supposed to be quite stable. While we try to offer
 as good a product as possible, &KOffice; is still a young project and will certainly
 mature in the next releases, when some parts are planned to be rewritten or replaced.
</para>
</answer></qandaentry>

<qandaentry><question><para> Are you going to implement feature XYZ?</para></question><answer>
<para>
First of all: certainly many features should be implemented in the future. However,
 &KOffice; is mainly based on the work of volunteers and thus it often lacks the manpower
 it needs to address many issues. If you are a developer and you lack a feature,
 consider helping us and talk to us on the mailing lists. Many features can be implemented
 independently of the &KOffice; main code base by implementing so-called plugins or
 data tools. &KOffice; developers are always willing to help you if you want to get
 your hands dirty!</para>
</answer></qandaentry>

<qandaentry><question><para> What do I need for using &KOffice;?</para></question><answer>
<para>
You should use the latest Qt library, i.e. 3.0.5 (see <ulink url="ftp://ftp.trolltech.com/qt/source/">
ftp://ftp.trolltech.com/qt/source/</ulink>) and the latest <ulink url="http://www.kde.org">KDE
 libraries</ulink> (eg. 3.0.3 for &KOffice; 1.2; the next &KOffice; release will require
 KDE 3.1 and Qt 3.1). If you are compiling a development version from CVS, this information
 is not up-to-date anymore; consult the <ulink url="http://lists.kde.org">mailing list 
 archives</ulink> of the koffice-devel list for information on the needed libraries or ask
 on the <ulink url="mailto:koffice at kde dot org">koffice</ulink> or 
 <ulink url="mailto:koffice-devel at kde dot org">koffice-devel</ulink> lists if you run into trouble.</para>
</answer></qandaentry>

<qandaentry><question><para> Which license applies to &KOffice;?</para></question><answer>
<para>
&KOffice; is an open-source project and completely free. Regarding the license, it
 was first put under GPL. Some programs have been moved to the AL
 (Artistic License), maybe others will follow. This license is less restrictive
 than the GPL, thus allowing linking certain (free but non-GPL) libs into
 it without raising legal issues for distributors etc.
 However, it's just as free as the GPL, in fact it is even more free.</para>

</answer></qandaentry>

<qandaentry><question><para> How do I report bugs?</para></question><answer>
<para>
Please report bugs to
<ulink url="http://bugs.kde.org">http://bugs.kde.org</ulink>.</para>
<para>
Please note, that bug reports like "It doesn't work" or "&KOffice; sucks" will neither
 help nor get you nice responses. A good bug report includes (if possible) things like:
<orderedlist>
<listitem><para>a description how to reproduce the bug.</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>maybe a backtrace.</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>if possible: information about library versions etc., if they seem to correlate to the problem.</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>best of all: a patch!</para></listitem>
</orderedlist></para>

</answer></qandaentry>

<qandaentry><question><para>Can I use KOffice on Windows?</para></question>
<answer><para>
At the moment this isn't possible. But there is work going on in that direction,
as part of the <ulink url="http://kde-cygwin.sourceforge.net/">KDE Cygwin project</ulink>,
which is a port of Qt and KDE to Windows using Cygwin, the POSIX emulation 
layer for Windows, and the Cygwin XFree86 server.</para><para>
At the time of writing this, KOffice hasn't been ported yet.
</para></answer></qandaentry>


</qandadiv>

<qandadiv id="howtogetandinstall"><title>How to get and install &KOffice;</title>

<qandaentry><question><para> How do I get and compile the &KOffice; sources?</para></question><answer>
<para>
Please have a look at <ulink url="http://koffice.kde.org/install-source.phtml">
http://koffice.kde.org/install-source.phtml</ulink> </para>

</answer></qandaentry><qandaentry><question><para> I want to be on the bleeding edge. How can I get my sources up to date?</para></question><answer>
<para>
The easiest way to keep your &KOffice; sources up to date is using <application>cvsup</application>.
 See
<ulink url="http://www.kde.org/cvsup.html">http://www.kde.org/cvsup.html</ulink> for
 details on how to set it up. You'll need to checkout the module
 <filename>koffice</filename>. Please keep in mind that the versions in the development
 branch are not supposed to work stable.</para>

</answer></qandaentry>
<qandaentry><question><para> How do I install &KOffice; if I'm not root?</para></question><answer>
<para>
You've got to pass some directory where you've got write access (e.g. in your home directory)
 as prefix to configure. So you should type something like: <command>./configure --prefix=<replaceable>/home/jdoe/foo/bar</replaceable></command>
 plus of course other options you might want to pass to configure. Then of course you
 don't have to do <command>su -c "make install"</command>, but just <command>make install</command>.</para>
</answer></qandaentry>
<qandaentry><question><para> Where can I find information on compiling Qt or the KDE libs?</para></question><answer>
<para>
For Qt, have a look at the file <filename>INSTALL</filename> in your Qt root directory.</para>
<para>
See
<ulink url="http://www.kde.org/documentation/faq/index.html">http://www.kde.org/documentation/faq/index.html</ulink>
 for details on KDE.</para>
</answer></qandaentry>

<qandaentry><question><para> What binary distributions are there and where do I find them?</para></question><answer>
<para>
You can find up-to-date information on available binaries <ulink url="http://www.koffice.org/install-binaries.phtml">here</ulink>.</para>

</answer></qandaentry><qandaentry><question><para> How do I install binary RPMs?</para></question><answer>
<para>
Type the following as root: <command>rpm -U <replaceable>koffice.rpm</replaceable></command>. Please replace <replaceable>koffice.rpm</replaceable>
 with the full path to and the name of your binary rpm.</para>

</answer></qandaentry><qandaentry><question><para> Is &KOffice; available on CD?</para></question><answer>
<para>
Most linux distributions by now ship &KOffice;. So if you have an up-to-date
 linux distribution, you probably are lucky.  I don't know of any other operating
 system vendors who ship &KOffice; and I don't know about any separate CDs.
 The &KOffice; project itself does not sell any CD-ROMs.
</para>
</answer></qandaentry>
</qandadiv>

<qandadiv id="problemscomp"><title>Problems compiling &KOffice; </title>

<qandaentry><question><para> What should I do if problems occur?</para></question><answer>
<para>
If problems occur during compiling, please:
<itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>check the problems mentioned in this section</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>check whether you are using a recent kdelibs package (KDE v3.0.x).</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>check whether you are using the <emphasis>correct versions</emphasis> of all required packages:
 you need Qt v3.0.x.
In case this FAQ is outdated, better check
<ulink
url="http://koffice.kde.org/install-source.phtml">
http://koffice.kde.org/install-source.phtml</ulink> for  requirements,
too.</para></listitem> <listitem><para>check if you compiled all libs with
one compiler.</para></listitem> <listitem><para>check if you're compiling
with a recent gcc
</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>if it
compiled for you before, but now, after some updates, doesn't anymore:
remove all <filename>.deps</filename>-directories in your koffice source
tree and try again (<command>make  maintainer-clean</command> is the
safest, I think).</para></listitem> <listitem><para>After you've checked
all this and the problems still persist, contact
<email>koffice at kde dot org</email>. Include information  about your system as
well as the remark that you've read the FAQ and it didn't  help. If
configure failed, include your <emphasis>config.log</emphasis>.
</para></listitem> </itemizedlist></para> <para> Please
<emphasis>don't</emphasis> contact the mailing list in case of:
<itemizedlist> <listitem><para>"internal compiler errors". This most likely
isn't a &KOffice; problem.</para></listitem> </itemizedlist></para>

</answer></qandaentry>
<qandaentry><question><para> I do <command>make -f Makefile.cvs</command> and get <computeroutput>aclocal not found</computeroutput>.</para></question><answer>
<para>(This only applies to the snapshots)
You haven't installed automake. Install automake (and make sure it's a recent version).
 For the snapshots, this problem is hopefully going to be solved so that there's no
 <filename>Makefile.cvs</filename> in the snapshots anymore.</para>

</answer></qandaentry><qandaentry><question><para> The <filename>configure</filename>" script is missing!</para></question><answer>
<para>(This only applies to the snapshots)
Please start with <command>make -f Makefile.cvs</command>. You should find <filename>configure</filename> now.</para>

</answer></qandaentry>

